In TypeScript, you can indicate that a type is "in practice" a certain type by using the `any` type. The `any` type is used to indicate that a value is of a type that is a subtype of any other type. It's a way to signal that the value is of a type that has certain properties, even if it may not be strictly typed.

Here's an example to illustrate:

```typescript
type Int = number;
type String = string | undefined;

// This will be of type string, even though it may be an integer
const value1: Int = 42;

// This will be of type string, even though it may be an integer
const value2: String = "Hello";

// This will be of type string, even though it may be an undefined
const value3: any = null;
```

In this example:
- `value1` is of type `string` because it is a string literal.
- `value2` is of type `string` because it is a string literal.
- `value3` is of type `any` because it can be an `undefined`.

Using `any` in this way communicates that the type can be any of the specified types, but in practice, it will always be one of those types.

