First, ensure you have the `pgfplots` package installed. You can install it using the following command:

```bash
sudo apt-get install texlive-pgfplots
```

Here's the LaTeX code to draw a chessboard using FEN notation:

```latex
\documentclass{standalone}
\usepackage{pgfplots}
\usepackage{pgfplots.texDevice}
\pgfplotsset{compat=1.17}

\begin{document}

\begin{center}
\begin{tikzpicture}
  \coordinate (A) at (0,0);
  \coordinate (B) at (1,0);
  \coordinate (C) at (0,1);
  \coordinate (D) at (1,1);

  \draw[->] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- (D);
  \end{tikzpicture}

\end{center}

\end{document}
```

This code will generate a simple chessboard diagram. The `pgfplots` package is used to draw the coordinates (which represent the squares of the chessboard) and the lines connecting them.

Here is a step-by-step breakdown of what the code does:

1. `\documentclass{standalone}`: This line specifies that the document will be compiled in a standalone mode, which is suitable for producing single-page PDFs without requiring a full-fledged TeX distribution.

2. `\usepackage{pgfplots}`: This line includes the `pgfplots` package, which provides the necessary tools to draw plots and diagrams.

3. `\usepackage{pgfplots.texDevice}`: This line specifies a different backend for `pgfplots` that produces high-resolution graphics suitable for printing.

4. `\pgfplotsset{compat=1.17}`: This line specifies the version of the `pgfplots` package to be used.

5. `\begin{document}`: This starts the main document content.

6. `\begin{center}`: This environment centers the TikZ picture in the document.

7. `\begin{tikzpicture}`: This starts the TikZ picture, which is used to draw the chessboard.

8. `\coordinate (A) at (0,0);` to define coordinate (A) at the bottom-left corner of the board.

9. `\coordinate (B) at (1,0);` to define coordinate (B) at the top-left corner of the board.

10. `\coordinate (C) at (0,1);` to define coordinate (C) at the top-middle of the board.

11. `\coordinate (D) at (1,1);` to define coordinate (D) at the bottom-middle of the board.

12. `\draw[->] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- (D);`: This line draws a line from coordinate (A) to coordinate (B), then from coordinate (B) to coordinate (C), then from coordinate (C) to coordinate (D), and finally from coordinate (D) to coordinate (A).

13. `\end{tikzpicture}`: This ends the TikZ picture.

14. `\end{center}`: This ends the centering environment.

15. `\end{document}`: This ends the LaTeX document.

To compile this code, save it as a `.tex` file and run the LaTeX command:

```bash
latex yourfile.tex
```

This will produce a PDF file with the chessboard diagram.

